Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.840 --> 00:00:04.029
Prof: Okay,
so last time we saw the

00:00:04.029 --> 00:00:07.340
jeopardy approach to solving the
Schrödinger equation,

00:00:07.340 --> 00:00:11.180
which is to take the answer and
find out what the problem was,

00:00:11.180 --> 00:00:14.610
and we saw that for a constant
potential you got a sine wave.

00:00:14.610 --> 00:00:17.848
You could choose any length of
sine wave you wanted,

00:00:17.848 --> 00:00:19.690
any wave period you wanted.
 

00:00:19.690 --> 00:00:22.475
It just turned out to be
different energies and it had a

00:00:22.475 --> 00:00:25.210
relationship between the
wavelength and the energy,

00:00:25.210 --> 00:00:27.961
the kinetic energy,
or the total energy in that

00:00:27.961 --> 00:00:28.380
case.
 

00:00:28.380 --> 00:00:35.530
And we saw an exponential is --
corresponds to --

00:00:35.530 --> 00:00:39.129
negative kinetic energy,
which not very many people in

00:00:39.129 --> 00:00:42.539
the class liked,
and not very many people ever

00:00:42.539 --> 00:00:44.945
like it,
but suck it up because that's

00:00:44.945 --> 00:00:47.660
the way kinetic energy is for
small particles.

00:00:47.660 --> 00:00:51.710
If you don't like to call it
kinetic energy because you're so

00:00:51.710 --> 00:00:55.760
wedded to the fact that for big
things it's ½mv^2,

00:00:55.760 --> 00:00:59.396
then just consider it the
difference between total energy

00:00:59.396 --> 00:01:00.890
and potential energy.
 

00:01:00.890 --> 00:01:02.049
Okay?
 

00:01:02.049 --> 00:01:04.930
But anyhow it's kinetic energy.
 

00:01:04.930 --> 00:01:06.668
Okay, so we looked at the
jeopardy approach,

00:01:06.668 --> 00:01:08.610
to start with the answer and
get the question.

00:01:08.610 --> 00:01:12.027
But we'd a lot rather do it the
other direction,

00:01:12.027 --> 00:01:16.390
to start with the problem and
find out what the answer is.

00:01:16.390 --> 00:01:19.450
And you can do that by guessing
the energy.

00:01:19.450 --> 00:01:22.599
If you have a sufficiently
simple system,

00:01:22.599 --> 00:01:25.830
that is, one particle in one
dimension;

00:01:25.830 --> 00:01:28.676
and this is a great way to get
the idea of what's special about

00:01:28.676 --> 00:01:31.647
quantum mechanics,
make it as simple as possible

00:01:31.647 --> 00:01:34.420
and then we'll go to realistic
systems.

00:01:34.420 --> 00:01:37.190
Okay, so we can rearrange the
Schrödinger equation.

00:01:37.190 --> 00:01:39.949
Remember, this is the
Schrödinger equation:

00:01:39.949 --> 00:01:43.411
HΨ=EΨ;
divide through by Ψ

00:01:43.411 --> 00:01:46.367
and split the
HΨ/Ψ part into

00:01:46.367 --> 00:01:50.492
the potential energy part,
V, which is a nothing,

00:01:50.492 --> 00:01:54.315
it's given to you,
and the kinetic energy part,

00:01:54.315 --> 00:01:59.360
which is a negative constant
that involves the inverse mass

00:01:59.360 --> 00:02:03.709
times the curvature of Ψ
over Ψ.

00:02:03.709 --> 00:02:06.790
So it has to do with the
shape of Ψ.

00:02:06.790 --> 00:02:08.625
And remember,
if you multiply Ψ by

00:02:08.625 --> 00:02:10.830
a constant,
you multiply the curvature by

00:02:10.830 --> 00:02:13.867
the same constant,
so the kinetic energy stays the

00:02:13.867 --> 00:02:14.240
same.
 

00:02:14.240 --> 00:02:17.990
So it's only what we say,
the shape, not really the

00:02:17.990 --> 00:02:21.889
amplitude, because that scales
with the curvature.

00:02:21.889 --> 00:02:26.688
Okay, but now we can rearrange
this, this way.

00:02:26.688 --> 00:02:33.490
So we have a formula here for
the curvature of Ψ.

00:02:33.490 --> 00:02:37.878
Now if you have a formula for
the curvature,

00:02:37.878 --> 00:02:41.050
if you know how a curve is
going to change,

00:02:41.050 --> 00:02:44.128
how a line is going to change
its curvature ,

00:02:44.128 --> 00:02:47.430
then you have a recipe for
drawing it,

00:02:47.430 --> 00:02:49.740
if you know how to start.
 

00:02:49.740 --> 00:02:52.660
If you start with a certain
height,

00:02:52.660 --> 00:02:56.288
and a certain slope -- suppose
you know that,

00:02:56.288 --> 00:03:00.568
and you know the curvature,
at that point,

00:03:00.568 --> 00:03:04.574
then you know if you take a
little step in that direction

00:03:04.574 --> 00:03:07.219
what the next slope is going to
be.

00:03:07.219 --> 00:03:07.830
Okay?
 

00:03:07.830 --> 00:03:09.658
Because that's how curved it is.
 

00:03:09.658 --> 00:03:13.310
And if you recalculate and know
the curvature at that point,

00:03:13.310 --> 00:03:15.451
then you know what the
curvature at the next point is

00:03:15.451 --> 00:03:16.808
going to be,
and the next and the next and

00:03:16.808 --> 00:03:19.230
the next,
and you can use this to just

00:03:19.230 --> 00:03:23.514
draw a curve that's bound to
satisfy the Schrödinger

00:03:23.514 --> 00:03:28.179
equation because you're using
the Schrödinger equation to

00:03:28.179 --> 00:03:29.479
generate it.
 

00:03:29.479 --> 00:03:30.479
Does everybody see this?
 

00:03:30.479 --> 00:03:32.568
This is really important.
 

00:03:32.568 --> 00:03:35.628
Do you want me to say it again,
or you got it now?

00:03:35.628 --> 00:03:38.400
If you have a formula for the
curvature --

00:03:38.400 --> 00:03:41.419
that's how fast the slope is
changing --

00:03:41.419 --> 00:03:45.889
and if you know the initial
height and the initial slope,

00:03:45.889 --> 00:03:48.405
then if you know the direction
of the slope you know where the

00:03:48.405 --> 00:03:49.560
next point is going to be.
 

00:03:49.560 --> 00:03:52.330
So you go to that -- just think
a tiny -- now this gets a

00:03:52.330 --> 00:03:53.520
problem in a computer.
 

00:03:53.520 --> 00:03:57.669
If the thing is really going
like this and you take a finite

00:03:57.669 --> 00:04:01.680
step, the slope will have
changed during your step and you

00:04:01.680 --> 00:04:03.650
won't get it just right.
 

00:04:03.650 --> 00:04:06.950
So you'll have to take smaller
and smaller steps so that it

00:04:06.950 --> 00:04:08.830
doesn't change during the step.
 

00:04:08.830 --> 00:04:09.538
Chenyu?
 

00:04:09.538 --> 00:04:11.370
Student: 
&gt;

00:04:11.370 --> 00:04:12.460
Prof: Can't hear very
well.

00:04:12.460 --> 00:04:14.092
Student:  Are you saying
that the curvature is a second

00:04:14.092 --> 00:04:14.438
derivative?
 

00:04:14.438 --> 00:04:16.680
Prof: Yes,
the curvature is a second

00:04:16.680 --> 00:04:17.639
derivative, yes.
 

00:04:17.639 --> 00:04:19.639
Student:  How do we
start with the correct slope?

00:04:19.639 --> 00:04:21.319
Prof: We'll get to that.
 

00:04:21.319 --> 00:04:24.442
But if you have the initial
slope, and the initial height,

00:04:24.442 --> 00:04:27.622
then you use the formula for
the curvature to trace out the

00:04:27.622 --> 00:04:28.170
curve.
 

00:04:28.170 --> 00:04:30.110
Everybody got that now?
 

00:04:30.110 --> 00:04:35.894
Okay, so that's great,
and it would be tedious to do

00:04:35.894 --> 00:04:38.833
this by hand,
but that's what this little

00:04:38.833 --> 00:04:41.333
program,
Erwin Meets Goldilocks,

00:04:41.333 --> 00:04:44.250
does is start the curve and
draw it out,

00:04:44.250 --> 00:04:47.714
according to what -- if you
know everything else in the

00:04:47.714 --> 00:04:48.420
equation.
 

00:04:48.420 --> 00:04:53.084
Okay, so, and remember it
curves away from zero when the

00:04:53.084 --> 00:04:57.579
potential energy is greater than
the total energy,

00:04:57.579 --> 00:05:02.096
and it curves towards zero when
the potential energy is less

00:05:02.096 --> 00:05:03.781
than the total energy.
 

00:05:03.781 --> 00:05:04.470
Right?
 

00:05:04.470 --> 00:05:08.899
So the potential energy being
greater than the total energy is

00:05:08.899 --> 00:05:12.252
a bad situation intuitively,
right, it means the kinetic

00:05:12.252 --> 00:05:14.540
energy is negative,
and it curves away from the

00:05:14.540 --> 00:05:15.069
baseline.
 

00:05:15.069 --> 00:05:18.550
And what's bad about that,
or dangerous about that?

00:05:18.550 --> 00:05:19.350
Yes, Kevin?
 

00:05:19.350 --> 00:05:20.509
Pardon me?
 

00:05:20.509 --> 00:05:22.000
Student:  It's not
bounded.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:24.610
Prof: Yes,
it'll keep going until it gets

00:05:24.610 --> 00:05:26.610
to infinity, if it's curving
away.

00:05:26.610 --> 00:05:31.019
Okay, and that's not allowed,
it has to not go to infinity.

00:05:31.019 --> 00:05:33.240
Okay, so now do we know
everything else?

00:05:33.240 --> 00:05:35.379
Well we know m, the mass.
 

00:05:35.379 --> 00:05:38.297
We know the constant,
C, and the V is

00:05:38.297 --> 00:05:41.505
given to us, the potential
energy changes with position.

00:05:41.505 --> 00:05:42.089
Right?
 

00:05:42.089 --> 00:05:44.730
But we know how it changes with
position;

00:05:44.730 --> 00:05:47.851
it's Coulomb's law typically,
or we can do some other law if

00:05:47.851 --> 00:05:48.540
we want to.
 

00:05:48.540 --> 00:05:53.704
So this recipe then,
you know everything on the

00:05:53.704 --> 00:05:57.410
right, except the total energy.
 

00:05:57.410 --> 00:06:00.456
Ψ you don't care
about because you can scale it,

00:06:00.456 --> 00:06:03.029
you can make it anything you
want, call it one.

00:06:03.029 --> 00:06:04.379
Okay?
 

00:06:04.379 --> 00:06:06.310
Then we can double it if we
want to or whatever.

00:06:06.310 --> 00:06:07.540
So Ψ we know;
m we know;

00:06:07.540 --> 00:06:09.439
C we know;
V we know.

00:06:09.439 --> 00:06:12.040
We're going to guess E.
 

00:06:12.040 --> 00:06:15.670
So that means if we know the
initial slope --

00:06:15.670 --> 00:06:19.620
and for the problems we work on
the initial slope will be zero,

00:06:19.620 --> 00:06:24.785
and you'll see why -- then we
can use this formula to trace

00:06:24.785 --> 00:06:26.209
out the curve.
 

00:06:26.209 --> 00:06:26.850
Okay?
 

00:06:26.850 --> 00:06:28.310
And that's what the computer
does for you.

00:06:28.310 --> 00:06:31.410
So people were worried last
night about math.

00:06:31.410 --> 00:06:33.310
Don't worry about math.
 

00:06:33.310 --> 00:06:38.074
Let the computer calculate how
these slopes change and so on.

00:06:38.074 --> 00:06:38.709
Right?
 

00:06:38.709 --> 00:06:41.569
All you have to do is think
about the curvature.

00:06:41.569 --> 00:06:43.290
Okay?
 

00:06:43.290 --> 00:06:45.410
So you just have to think about
the graph.

00:06:45.410 --> 00:06:48.624
Okay, so we're going to talk
now about nodes and

00:06:48.624 --> 00:06:50.675
quantization,
in one dimension,

00:06:50.675 --> 00:06:54.300
using this program Erwin
Meets Goldilocks.

00:06:54.300 --> 00:06:56.389
And there's a problem set for
Monday,

00:06:56.389 --> 00:06:58.434
as you know,
where you do this,

00:06:58.434 --> 00:07:00.819
and the answers are on the
Wiki,

00:07:00.819 --> 00:07:03.709
but don't look at them before
you've given it a good try.

00:07:03.709 --> 00:07:07.923
Okay, so let's -- there are
simpler things to start with,

00:07:07.923 --> 00:07:12.213
like a constant potential
energy or running into a wall or

00:07:12.213 --> 00:07:14.319
into a pillow more like.
 

00:07:14.319 --> 00:07:18.889
But the harmonic oscillator,
or Hooke's law,

00:07:18.889 --> 00:07:23.569
is a very popular one to do;
so we're going to do that.

00:07:23.569 --> 00:07:25.946
Okay, so here we're looking at
the potential energy as a

00:07:25.946 --> 00:07:26.939
function of distance.
 

00:07:26.939 --> 00:07:30.673
And also on the -- so you see
the distance goes from zero to

00:07:30.673 --> 00:07:34.661
two and a half angstroms and the
potential energy goes from zero

00:07:34.661 --> 00:07:36.750
to 100 kilocalories per mole.
 

00:07:36.750 --> 00:07:40.040
You can change that if you want
to on the computer.

00:07:40.040 --> 00:07:40.949
Okay?
 

00:07:40.949 --> 00:07:46.290
And the horizontal black line
is a completely different plot.

00:07:46.290 --> 00:07:48.050
It's a plot of Ψ.
 

00:07:48.050 --> 00:07:51.764
That's the plot on top of this
one where we're going to trace

00:07:51.764 --> 00:07:53.190
out the wavefunction.
 

00:07:53.190 --> 00:07:53.720
Okay?
 

00:07:53.720 --> 00:07:56.230
And that's zero of the
wavefunction;

00:07:56.230 --> 00:07:58.709
here's zero of energy.
 

00:07:58.709 --> 00:07:59.990
Okay?
 

00:07:59.990 --> 00:08:03.583
And the reason we put them on
top of one another is so that

00:08:03.583 --> 00:08:06.930
it's easy to see the influence
of one on the other,

00:08:06.930 --> 00:08:11.490
of the wavefunction on the
potential energy and vice-versa,

00:08:11.490 --> 00:08:14.189
and because they're functions
of the same thing.

00:08:14.189 --> 00:08:16.180
What's Ψ a function
of?

00:08:16.180 --> 00:08:17.579
What's it a function of?
 

00:08:17.579 --> 00:08:19.829
Students:  Position.
 

00:08:19.829 --> 00:08:21.759
Prof: It's a function of
the position.

00:08:21.759 --> 00:08:23.879
Position of what?
 

00:08:23.879 --> 00:08:25.910
The one particle we're talking
about.

00:08:25.910 --> 00:08:27.189
Okay?
 

00:08:27.189 --> 00:08:29.740
And the potential energy is
also a function of the position.

00:08:29.740 --> 00:08:35.330
Okay, so the way we're going to
do this then is to guess an

00:08:35.330 --> 00:08:39.668
energy, let the computer trace
out this curve,

00:08:39.668 --> 00:08:42.558
and see whether it's okay.
 

00:08:42.558 --> 00:08:45.100
What will tell us whether it's
okay?

00:08:45.100 --> 00:08:49.879
How will we know if it's okay?
 

00:08:49.879 --> 00:08:51.658
It's got to be continuous.
 

00:08:51.658 --> 00:08:53.620
We're not going to have a
problem with that because the

00:08:53.620 --> 00:08:55.000
computer is tracing it out this
way;

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:56.980
it's not going to be
discontinuous.

00:08:56.980 --> 00:09:00.596
But the main thing is that it
doesn't diverge,

00:09:00.596 --> 00:09:03.250
that it doesn't go to infinity.
 

00:09:03.250 --> 00:09:08.129
Okay, so let's just guess
twenty-one kcal/mole.

00:09:08.129 --> 00:09:09.190
Why not?
 

00:09:09.190 --> 00:09:12.871
Okay, now you can already tell
me something about what the

00:09:12.871 --> 00:09:14.808
curve is going to look like.
 

00:09:14.808 --> 00:09:19.230
Notice that at those two
distances, between these two

00:09:19.230 --> 00:09:23.903
distances, the total energy is
higher than the potential

00:09:23.903 --> 00:09:24.840
energy.
 

00:09:24.840 --> 00:09:29.788
What's the curve going to look
like in that region?

00:09:29.788 --> 00:09:32.899
The kinetic energy is going to
be positive, right?

00:09:32.899 --> 00:09:38.200
What will the curve look like?
 

00:09:38.200 --> 00:09:39.408
Pat?
 

00:09:39.408 --> 00:09:40.970
Student:  Spike up in
between them.

00:09:40.970 --> 00:09:41.580
Prof: Can't hear very
