00:09:41.580 --> 00:09:44.009
Student:  It's going to
spike up in between those two

00:09:44.009 --> 00:09:44.340
lines.
 

00:09:44.340 --> 00:09:47.539
Prof: It may go up,
it may go down.

00:09:47.539 --> 00:09:48.379
Yes?
 

00:09:48.379 --> 00:09:50.610
Pardon me?
 

00:09:50.610 --> 00:09:53.610
It's not -- would it be a sine
curve?

00:09:53.610 --> 00:09:56.210
Does anybody think it wouldn't
be a sine curve?

00:09:56.210 --> 00:09:57.009
Why not Russell?
 

00:09:57.009 --> 00:09:59.472
Student:  It does
sinusoidal behavior when the

00:09:59.472 --> 00:10:00.610
potential is constant.
 

00:10:00.610 --> 00:10:02.750
Prof: That's when the
potential is constant.

00:10:02.750 --> 00:10:05.311
It's not constant through here.
 

00:10:05.311 --> 00:10:05.889
Right?
 

00:10:05.889 --> 00:10:09.028
So it won't be an exact sine
curve.

00:10:09.028 --> 00:10:12.346
If this isn't very high,
it might be close to a sine

00:10:12.346 --> 00:10:14.883
curve because it's sort of
constant-ish,

00:10:14.883 --> 00:10:17.288
if this is a very small
distance.

00:10:17.288 --> 00:10:21.139
But what characteristic must it
have?

00:10:21.139 --> 00:10:22.759
Student:  It'll curve
towards zero.

00:10:22.759 --> 00:10:23.460
Prof: Say it again.
 

00:10:23.460 --> 00:10:25.308
Student:  It'll curve
towards zero.

00:10:25.308 --> 00:10:26.970
Prof: It'll curve
towards zero.

00:10:26.970 --> 00:10:29.490
So it might -- it'll look
something like this.

00:10:29.490 --> 00:10:31.851
Always -- it's curving and
going up and down,

00:10:31.851 --> 00:10:34.322
maybe going high,
but it's always curving to go

00:10:34.322 --> 00:10:35.879
back toward the baseline.
 

00:10:35.879 --> 00:10:38.070
It's never going to go to
infinity.

00:10:38.070 --> 00:10:39.168
Okay?
 

00:10:39.168 --> 00:10:43.081
Now, there's a problem,
because if you go the other

00:10:43.081 --> 00:10:45.072
way,
the rest of the graph,

00:10:45.072 --> 00:10:49.009
the kinetic energy is negative
because the potential's higher

00:10:49.009 --> 00:10:50.190
than the total.
 

00:10:50.190 --> 00:10:54.912
So in that region there's great
danger that the line is going to

00:10:54.912 --> 00:10:57.836
go to infinity,
because it's going to be

00:10:57.836 --> 00:11:00.460
curving away from the baseline.
 

00:11:00.460 --> 00:11:01.889
Okay?
 

00:11:01.889 --> 00:11:05.190
Now how could you possibly
avoid that?

00:11:05.190 --> 00:11:09.947
How could you have it such that
the curvature divided by the

00:11:09.947 --> 00:11:14.865
value of the wavefunction gets
very big and the curvature away

00:11:14.865 --> 00:11:18.611
from the baseline,
but still it doesn't go to

00:11:18.611 --> 00:11:19.340
infinity?
 

00:11:19.340 --> 00:11:23.405
How can the kinetic energy be
big and negative,

00:11:23.405 --> 00:11:27.472
the curvature divided by the
value is enormous,

00:11:27.472 --> 00:11:30.480
but it doesn't go to infinity?
 

00:11:30.480 --> 00:11:33.379
How can that be?
 

00:11:33.379 --> 00:11:35.409
Student:  Do we have to
